My name is Khan(칸). I am a tattoo(타투) artist from South Korea. I have been professionally tattooing since 2001. I never imagined that I would be a tattoo artist until I saw the traditional Japanese tattoo. Actually, I wanted to be an Architect like Antonio Gaudi.( It is still one of my dreams though :D) One day I met Japanese Yakuza, who has traditional Japanese tattoo. It was amazing and inspiring as a piece of art on human's body. I think that was a turning point in my life. First I started to practice on my whole body. Then I opened my own studio in Tokyo and became a tattoo artist. As a foreigner It was not an easy to be a traditional tattoo artist in Japan. But it has been a decision I had never regretted. Tattooist is the most awesome job in the world. Lately, I have been doing a lot of color realism and My style called Neo-Fantasy, attending various conventions and doing many guest spots in studios in both Europe and the United States. I travel a lot and enjoy working with my friends and artists from overseas. These experiences have been and always will be precious moments of my life. I am still learning a lot from my works and always think my best art is my next one! description._content:
Tattoo by Jason at Living Canvas Tattoo in Tempe, Arizona

My first tattoo!  This is a painting that my grandmother did along time ago.  It is her version of a famous chinese scroll painting.  I have wanted to get a tattoo for a long time, but I could never come up with anything that I wanted to have on me forever.  Interpret however you would like.  To me the poet stands as a reminder to me to stop and enjoy how wonderful life can be.  The cherry blossom reminds me that I need to never take anything for granted because you never know how long things will be around.

My first tattoo, its the Zodiac Scorpio, which happens to be my symbol (duh!).  It was a total coincidence that I found this symbol-I was searching for a symbol that represents determination and strong will and what do you know-its the sign I was born under.

I got the tattoo in July 2006 at Lost Art in Salt Lake City.

So I always wanted to get a tattoo commemorating my stint as a US Navy DeepSea Diver. After all, I had to overcome my greatest fear to achieve this milestone. Um, yes, I was afraid of water even when I was in Dive School. Not all water like a swimming pool but open water like a lake, river, ocean, etc. If I couldn't see the bottom it didn't matter if it was 2 feet or 2 thousand feet it scared the shit out of me. Naturally that was a bit of a problem but it was just something I had to do. And given that a percentage of 1 % of the people that try to be Navy Divers, Navy SEALS or Navy EOD (Explosive Ordinance Disposal) Specialists actually make it from the beginning to end of the program I have to admit that I'm pretty proud of being part of that percentage! Yes, I was a really cocky asshole for most of my military career! :-D Anywho, I thought it was appropriate for the cocky US Navy Diver to have a mermaid on his back. So I designed the tattoo to have the elusive and possibly make believe beauty of the sea holding Poseidon's trident (cuz we all know it's the ladies that are really in charge) and holding a diver's head still in the helmet! And the numbers at the bottom are my class number. She's got a nice rack, huh?! ;-)

Also, I edited these pics in such a way as to really exaggerate the ink to make the tattoos pop!  :-)

2010's been an extremely important year for me. And I couldn't have done the things I've done, seen the things I've seen, or experiences all the things I have without a group of friends that I now call family. This one's for you, Josh, Zach, Austin, Liam, Sam, Darius, Tim, & Dan. Mostly inspired by "Change Of Time", "Lantern", & "Another New World". All of which are beautiful songs, but each one hit me in a direct and deeply personal way throughout my year. You guys should see this thing in person. Sorry for the garish watermark.
